========================================================================
SECTION 5 -- Mathematical Analysis
========================================================================

  FINDING: Among all 120 600-cell vertices, S_4-preserving vertices
  are EXACTLY those where beta is an integer, i.e., the x=y=z=0 case.

  PROOF SKETCH:
    beta = 299 + w + sqrt(phi)*[phi/2*x + 1/(2phi)*(y-z)]
    ||p*beta|| = ||p*299 + p*w + p*sqrt(phi)*[phi/2*x + (y-z)/(2phi)]||
               = ||p*w + p*sqrt(phi)*[phi/2*x + (y-z)/(2phi)]||
    (since p*299 is always an integer)

    For x = y = z = 0: ||p*beta|| = ||p*w||.
      If w is integer: ||p*w|| = 0 < 1/p for all p. S_4 trivially preserved.
      If w = +-1/2: ||p*w|| = ||p/2||. For p=2: ||1|| = 0 < 1/2. For p=3: ||3/2||=1/2 >= 1/3. FAIL.

    For (x,y,z) != (0,0,0): sqrt(phi) is transcendental (algebraically independent
    of 1 over Q), so p*sqrt(phi)*[...] is generically irrational and ||.|| is
    pseudo-random. The BC condition ||p*beta|| < 1/p for ALL p in {2,3,19,191}
    simultaneously requires extraordinary coincidence -- none found here.

  DEGENERATE CASE (beta = integer):
    For w in {+1,-1} and x=y=z=0: beta in {298, 300}.
    ||p*n|| = 0 for any integer n and any prime p. S_beta = ALL primes.
    C(S_beta cap [2,1000]) = 962.609151 >> 2*sqrt(33) = 11.489125
    Certifies g <= 231654 (trivially, for any integer beta).

  CONCLUSION:
    The 600-cell geometry, as parameterized by this formula, does NOT produce
    new non-trivial BC-certified beta values beyond those already known.
    The integer-beta case is structure-independent: it works for ANY integer.
    Non-integer vertices do not preserve S_4 simultaneously for {2,3,19,191}.

  CERTIFIED BETA VALUES FROM 600-CELL:
    beta = 298.000000  [vertex (-1.0000,0.0000,0.0000,0.0000)]
      C(S_beta cap [2,1000]) = 962.609151  |  g_max = 231654  |  INTEGER-DEGENERATE
    beta = 300.000000  [vertex (1.0000,0.0000,0.0000,0.0000)]
      C(S_beta cap [2,1000]) = 962.609151  |  g_max = 231654  |  INTEGER-DEGENERATE

